#Text=Brian Palmes ( died 1519 )
#Text=Brian Palmes ( before 1467 – 1519 ) was an English landowner , justice of the assize and politician who sat in the House of Commons .
#Text=Early life
#Text=Palmes was the son eldest son and heir of William Palmes of Naburn and Eleanor , daughter of William Heslerton of Heslerton .
#Text=He was a member of the Palmes family , an ancient upper-gentry family that had been seated at Naburn Hall since the 13th century .
#Text=In about 1480 he and his younger brother Guy entered the Middle Temple , where both were to do well .

#Text=In 1496 he became recorder of York in succession to Sir William Fairfax , and in the following year was made a Freeman ; he proved more diligent in attending the York council than some recorders , twice supervising elections when a mayor died in office .
#Text=It was a measure of the city ’s satisfaction that in 1504 it appointed his brother , who was already a sergeant , to be " of counsel " at 20s .
#Text=a year .
#Text=His and his first wife ’s membership of the city ’s Corpus Christi guild , and his own of the merchants ’ guild , suggest that he engaged in trade .
#Text=When in December 1509 Palmes was elected to Parliament he at once resigned the recordership .

#Text=The city rarely elected its recorder and the choice of Palmes may have been influenced by his recent despatch to London with two aldermen , one of them his fellow-Member William Nelson , on unspecified business .

#Text=Unlike Nelson , he was not to be re-elected , perhaps because he was made a sergeant in 1510 , but his continued standing in the city and shire is reflected in his appointment to nine subsidy commissions between 1512 and 1515 .
#Text=Little of a personal nature has come to light about his later years .

#Text=In 1515 he presented his son George ( later Wolsey ’s confessor and a canon of York ) to the living of Sutton-upon-Derwent , Yorkshire , and in the following year he was named executor by his brother .
#Text=Family
#Text=Palmes married first Ellen Acclome , the daughter of John Acclome of Moreby Hall , Yorkshire .
#Text=His second wife was Anne Markenfield , daughter of Sir Thomas Markenfield of Markenfield Hall .
#Text=Palmes was the father of five children from his first marriage :
#Text=Nicholas Palmes ( d. 1551 ) , succeeded his father to Naburn Hall .
#Text=He married his cousin Johana , daughter of William Conyers of Sockburn Hall , who was the mother of his eldest son and heir , Brian .
#Text=He married secondly Susan , daughter of Sir Robert Waterton of Walton Hall , West Yorkshire .
#Text=George Palmes , died unmarried
#Text=William Palmes , died unmarried
#Text=Richard Palmes , died unmarried
#Text=Agnes Palmes , married in 1559 Sir William Babthorpe of Babthorpe and Osgodby .
#Text=They were the parents of two children .
#Text=Marston Moor signet ring

#Text=Palmes ' portrait depicts him wearing a signet ring on his index finger ; this ring was lost by his descendant in the Battle of Marston Moor and it was found during the 1860s when a farmer was ploughing the battle site . [ 1 ]
#Text=Death

#Text=In his own will of 31 October 1519 Palmes asked to be buried in his parish church of St. George , York , whither his body was to be escorted by friars from the four York houses and by members of the Corpus Christi guild , and to have prayers said for him and his family locally for seven years and at Roecliffe for ever .

#Text=He made numerous bequests of lands and goods to his family , and named as executors and residuary legatees his wife , Sir William Bulmer and Sir Guy Dawny , Thomas Langton and James Duffelde , gentlemen , Richard Ellis , clerk , and William Marshall .

#Text=The will was proved on 11 January 1520 and an inquisition post mortem held at York castle on 27 ( ? )April 1520 found that Palmes had died on 1 Oct. ( sic ) 1519 leaving as his heir a 20-year-old son Nicholas .
#Text=At his death Palmes held the manors of Naburn and Gate Fulford , and lands , some of them acquired recently , scattered over a wide area of Yorkshire . [ 2 ]
